author: @newbie8051
text: 25:51, tanh is more computationally intensive than sigmoid, see the formula for both functions, you'll notice that the exponential term appears twice in tanh, making it more difficult to computer.  Also sigmoid are not zero centered, this makes convergence slower Sigmoids and tanh functions also saturate often, making the gradient of the activation==0, which stops the learning process for neurons

author: @newbie8051
text: 16:44 In bootstrapping technique, we pick samples with replacement and in cross validation, samples are picked without replacement. Bootstrapping is an up-sampling technique, whereas cross validation is used to measure model performance.   Bootstrapping picks datapoints from the dataset, with replacement i.e. that the same datapoint can be picked again too.  For k-fold cross validation, we divide the data into k-folds (k-partitions) and iteratively take one group/partition as a test_set and others as the train_set. We evaluate the model for each iteration and the accuracy is the mean of all iterations.

author: @hashiharis8169
text: The interview questions are good and even the guy who is being interviewed is performing with confidence. But what I have a suggestion is, even though this interview had good questions, the way of conducting a professional interview should not be like this. An interview is not meant to stress the person who is being interviewed and confuse him. It is the responsibility of the interviewers to conduct an interview in the most peaceful calm way. We are humans and mistakes would be answered by everyone, anyone can be wrong, but the mistakes should not be pointed out in the middle of the interview, which inturn will drain the confidence of the interviewed guy. This kind of attitude is not expected from a professional interviewer. It becomes the responsibility of the interviewer too that if they point out a mistake they should correct the mistake by letting them know the concept or the right answer. Honestly, interviews are meant not to stress or pressurise the person or the people watching this mock interview. So it would be better to conduct such interviews in a modern way. Research the interview rules and post mock interview videos instead of pressurising the freshers. They do deserve a respect for their hardwork from the interviewers, even if they are not getting job atleast behave to them with a consideration as they are humans and not as a machine learning model trained with some stress parameters.

author: @arunmohan7841
text: * skweness measures how much your data is distorted.Right skweness means positive skweness and the mean will be greater than the median. To remove skweness u can apply log over it to normalize.  * Standard scalar normalize the data as x-mean/STDdev. While min max scalar make it betwee 0 to 1.  * gini impurity = 1 - sum(p(y)^2)  * n_estimators=30 can reduce variance more..since rf generally reduce variance...so there is a chance that it can underfit...Generally it depends on data.   * Machine learning over deep learning when we have less data and interpretability matters for our model.  * Activation functions like relu,sigmoid etc introduces non linearity to the network.  * We can SGD with  decay learning rate if we want to reduce it over iteration  * Another reason for up and down movement of loss can also  be due  to exploding gradient problem..
